=== ''Goop'' ===
{{main|Goop (company)}}

In September 2008, Paltrow launched the weekly lifestyle newsletter ''Goop'', encouraging readers to 'nourish the inner aspect'.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/22/fashion/22gwyneth.html|title=Martha, Oprah ... Gwyneth?|last=Morris|first=Bob |date=February 22, 2009|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 7, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; Goop has expanded into a web-based company, Goop.com. According to Paltrow, the company's name came from someone telling her successful internet companies have double O's in their name,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=How Goop's Haters Made Gwyneth Paltrow's Company Worth $250 Million |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/magazine/big-business-gwyneth-paltrow-wellness.html |website=nytimes.com|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=July 29, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; and &quot;is a nickname, like my name is G.P., so that is really where it came from. And I wanted it to be a word that means nothing and could mean anything.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=GOOP: It's a portal into Gwyneth Paltrow's life|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2009-01-06-paltrow-goop_N.htm|website=usatoday30.usatoday.com|publisher=USA Today |accessdate=July 29, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; Goop has expanded into [[e-commerce]], collaborating with fashion brands, launching [[pop-up shop]]s,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|last=Lieber|first=Chavie |title=Inside Goop, Gwyneth Paltrow's Growing Empire|url=https://www.racked.com/2015/7/21/9006055/goop-gwyneth-paltrow|work=[[Vox Media|Racked]]|date=July 21, 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt; launching a [[wellness (alternative medicine)|wellness]] summit,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite magazine |url=http://people.com/bodies/in-goop-health-gwyneth-paltrow-wellness-summit/|title=We Attended Gwyneth Paltrow's $500-a-Ticket Health Summit: These Are the Craziest Things We Witnessed|date=June 12, 2017|magazine=[[People.com]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; a print magazine,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/28/fashion/goop-conde-nast-magazine.html |title=Goop and Condé Nast Team Up on a Magazine|last=Safronova|first=Valeriya|date=April 28, 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=July 21, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; a podcast,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40535306/goop-expands-media-empire-with-gwyneth-hosted-podcast|title=Goop expands media empire with Gwyneth-hosted podcast|date=February 23, 2018|publisher=FastCompany}}&lt;/ref&gt; and a documentary series streamed on Netflix.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=the goop lab with Gwyneth Paltrow {{!}} Netflix Official Site|url=https://www.netflix.com/title/80244690|access-date=2020-07-12|website=www.netflix.com|language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Goop, and by extension Paltrow, have drawn criticism by showcasing expensive products&lt;ref name=lgpa!&gt;{{cite news|title=Leave Gwyneth Paltrow alone! Her website gives me joy |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/mar/23/gwyneth-paltrow-is-an-ethereal-being-not-of-this-world-thats-why-i-love-her|work=The Guardian|date=March 23, 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt; and promoting medically and scientifically impossible treatments, many of which have harmful consequences. The controversies have included [[vaginal steaming]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last=McKnight|first=Zoe|title=This Canadian doctor is going head-to-head with Gwyneth Paltrow over Goop|url=https://www.thestar.com/life/2017/07/18/meet-the-canadian-doctor-whos-taking-on-goop.html|website=Thestar.com|publisher=Toronto Star|accessdate=August 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805184336/https://www.thestar.com/life/2017/07/18/meet-the-canadian-doctor-whos-taking-on-goop.html|archive-date=August 5, 2017|url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt; the use of [[vaginal weightlifting|jade eggs]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2017/01/22/no-gwyneth-paltrow-women-should-not-put-jade-eggs-in-their-vaginas-gynecologist-says/|title=No, Gwyneth Paltrow, women should not put jade eggs in their vaginas, gynecologist says |last=Phillips|first=Kristine|date=January 22, 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=July 7, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://drjengunter.wordpress.com/2017/01/17/dear-gwyneth-paltrow-im-a-gyn-and-your-vaginal-jade-eggs-are-a-bad-idea/|title=Dear Gwyneth Paltrow, I'm a GYN and your vaginal jade eggs are a bad idea|last=Gunter|first=Jen |date=January 17, 2017|website=Dr. Jen Gunter|author-link=Jennifer Gunter |accessdate=July 7, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; a dangerous [[coffee enema]] device,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2018/01/gwyneth-paltrows-goop-wants-you-to-start-2018-right-with-a-135-coffee-enema/ |title=In &quot;triumph of ignorance,&quot; Gwyneth Paltrow's Goop touts $135 coffee enema |date=January 6, 2018 |accessdate=January 7, 2018 |first=Beth |last=Mole |website=[[Ars Technica]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last=Ernst|first=E |title=Colonic irrigation and the theory of autointoxication: a triumph of ignorance over science.|journal=Journal of Clinical Gastroenterology|date=June 1997|volume=24|issue=4 |pages=196–8|pmid=9252839|doi=10.1097/00004836-199706000-00002}}&lt;/ref&gt; and &quot;Body Vibes&quot;, wearable stickers that were claimed to &quot;rebalance the energy frequency in our bodies&quot; and which Goop falsely claimed were made of a [[NASA]]-developed material.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://goop.com/wearable-stickers-that-promote-healing-really/|title=Wearable Stickers that Promote Healing (Really!)|date=June 20, 2017 |website=Goop|accessdate=July 7, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/nasa-calls-bullshit-on-goops-120-bio-frequency-healing-1796309360|title=NASA Calls Bullshit on Goop's $120 'Bio-Frequency Healing' Sticker Packs|last=Paoletta|first=Rae |date=June 22, 2017|work=Gizmodo|accessdate=July 7, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; Goop settled a lawsuit regarding the health claims it made over the jade eggs.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last=Weaver |first=Matthew |title=Goop to pay out over unproven health benefits of vaginal eggs |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/sep/05/gwyneth-paltrow-goop-to-pay-out-over-unproven-health-benefits-of-vaginal-eggs |accessdate=September 5, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=September 5, 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Jill Avery]], a brand analyst, has noted how Goop's response to criticisms seems designed to &quot;strengthen their brand and draw their customers closer&quot;, noting Goop's references to [[feminism]], [[traditional Asian medicine]]s and [[Eastern philosophy|Eastern philosophies]], and [[anti-establishment]] politics to do so.&lt;ref name=Vox&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2017/7/19/15988180/gwyneth-paltrow-goop-jade-egg-debunkers|title=Is Gwyneth Paltrow's Goop pseudoscience winning? |last=Belluz|first=Julia|author-link=Julia Belluz|date=September 12, 2017|work=[[Vox.com]] |accessdate=December 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206140218/https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2017/7/19/15988180/gwyneth-paltrow-goop-jade-egg-debunkers|archive-date=December 6, 2017|url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On January 24, 2020, [[Netflix]] released ''[[The Goop Lab]],'' a [[documentary series]]. The 6-part show promotes [[Goop (company)|Goop]], and covers [[Pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] topics in [[Energy medicine|energy healing]], the use of [[psychedelic drug]]s, [[Cryotherapy|cold therapy]], [[Life extension|anti-aging]], [[mediumship]], and [[Human female sexuality|female sexuality]].&lt;ref name=tvline&gt;{{cite web |last1=Iannucci |first1=Rebecca |title=Gwyneth Paltrow's Goop Docuseries Gets January Premiere at Netflix |url=https://tvline.com/2020/01/06/gwyneth-paltrow-the-goop-lab-docuseries-premiere-date-netflix |website=[[TVLine]] |accessdate=January 6, 2020 |language=en |date=January 6, 2020}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=thecut&gt;{{cite web |last1=Arnold |first1=Amanda |title=Well, This Is Certainly Evocative |url=https://www.thecut.com/2020/01/gwyneth-paltrow-the-goop-lab-trailer.html |website=[[New York (magazine)#Digital expansion and blogs|The Cut]] |accessdate=January 9, 2020 |language=en-us |date=January 6, 2020}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=pastemagazine&gt;{{cite web |last1=Keene |first1=Allison |title=First Trailer for Netflix's The Goop Lab Honestly Asks &quot;How Can We Milk the S*** Out of This?&quot; |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2020/01/the-goop-lab-trailer-netflix.html |website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |accessdate=January 6, 2020 |language=en |date=January 6, 2020}}&lt;/ref&gt; Critics argued that granting Goop access to Netflix's platform was a &quot;win for [[pseudoscience]]&quot;.&lt;ref name = thedailybeast&gt;{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/scientists-are-pissed-that-netflix-is-legitimizing-gwyneth-paltrows-goop|title=Docs Are Pissed Netflix Is Giving Gwyneth's Goop a Megaphone|last=Basu|first=Tanya|date=February 5, 2019|access-date=3 April 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name = Bundel&gt;{{cite web |last1=Bundel |first1=Ani |title=Netflix's new partnership with Gwyneth Paltrow's Goop brand is a win for pseudoscience |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/netflix-s-new-partnership-gwyneth-paltrow-s-goop-brand-win-ncna969746 |publisher=NBC News |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190220201923/https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/netflix-s-new-partnership-gwyneth-paltrow-s-goop-brand-win-ncna969746 |archive-date=February 20, 2019 |date=February 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name = ars-goopseries&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/02/goop-lands-netflix-deal-despite-track-record-of-egregious-false-health-claims/|title=Netflix buys into Goop hooey with deal to make a wellness docuseries|last=Mole|first=Beth|date=February 5, 2019|website=Ars Technica|access-date=3 April 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; Upon release of the first [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]], and again after the full 6-episode series was available, the series received significant criticism concerning the medical and scientific misinformation it presented.&lt;ref name=Huffpo&gt;{{cite web |last1=Holmes |first1=Lindsay |title=Gwyneth Paltrow Brings Bad Health Advice To Netflix With 'The Goop Lab' |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/the-goop-lab-netflix_l_5e1360c4e4b0b2520d25870c |website=huffpost.com |publisher=Huffington Post |accessdate=12 January 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200112151143/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/the-goop-lab-netflix_l_5e1360c4e4b0b2520d25870c |archive-date=12 January 2020 |date=6 January 2020 |url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=wtm&gt;{{Cite AV media|url=https://omny.fm/shows/wait-theres-more/goop-lab-and-the-rise-of-the-wellness-industry|title=Goop Lab and the rise of the wellness industry|date=2020-01-15|last=Khandake|first=Tamara|type=podcast|language=en|publisher=Global News|series=Wait There's More|access-date=2020-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=PatheosWilde&gt;{{cite web |last1=Wilde |first1=Val |title=Gwyneth Paltrow's &quot;The Goop Lab&quot; Is Unscientific Garbage. Then It Gets Worse. |url=https://friendlyatheist.patheos.com/2020/01/20/gwyneth-paltrows-the-goop-lab-is-unscientific-garbage-then-it-gets-worse/ |website=Patheos.com |publisher=Patheos |accessdate=20 January 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200120225756/https://friendlyatheist.patheos.com/2020/01/20/gwyneth-paltrows-the-goop-lab-is-unscientific-garbage-then-it-gets-worse/ |archive-date=20 January 2020 |date=20 January 2020 |quote=Netflix and Gwyneth Paltrow have entered into an unholy alliance and spawned The Goop Lab, a (purported) health and wellness docu-series set for release on January 24. |url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=Beast&gt;{{cite web |last1=Bradley |first1=Laura |title=UK Health Chief Calls B.S. on Gwyneth Paltrow's 'Goop Lab' for Spreading 'Misinformation' |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/uk-health-chief-says-gwyneth-paltrows-netflix-show-goop-lap-is-full-of-misinformation?source=articles&amp;via=rss&amp;ut |website=Thedailybeast.com |publisher=The Daily Beast |accessdate=31 January 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200131230123/https://www.thedailybeast.com/uk-health-chief-says-gwyneth-paltrows-netflix-show-goop-lap-is-full-of-misinformation?source=articles&amp;via=rss&amp;ut |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |date=31 January 2020 |quote=NHS Chief Simon Stevens said the show elevates “dubious wellness products and dodgy procedures.” |url-status=live }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=NewScientist&gt;{{cite web |last1=Wilson |first1=Clare |title=Goop Lab on Netflix shows how easy it is to fall for bad science |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2230459-goop-lab-on-netflix-shows-how-easy-it-is-to-fall-for-bad-science/ |website=Newscientist.com |publisher=New Scientist |accessdate=28 January 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200128021309/https://www.newscientist.com/article/2230459-goop-lab-on-netflix-shows-how-easy-it-is-to-fall-for-bad-science/ |archive-date=January 28, 2020 |date=17 January 2020 |quote=Still, Goop was valued at a quarter of a billion dollars in 2018, so Paltrow has clearly found an effective business model. She was quoted in The New York Times as saying that controversies just led to more people visiting her website, letting her “monetise those eyeballs”. It’s hard not to suspect that criticism of The Goop Lab won’t bother Paltrow one bit. |url-status=live }}&lt;/ref&gt;

On January 27, 2020, Truth in Advertising watchdog (TINA.org) filed a complaint with the district attorneys of California alleging that Goop has continued to engage in deceptive marketing.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/02/goop-violating-court-order-with-yet-more-bogus-health-claims-watchdog-says/|title=Goop accused of more deceptive health claims, violating court order|last=Mole|first=Beth|date=2020-02-03|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-02-04}}&lt;/ref&gt; TINA.org's complaint alleges that Goop claims their products are &quot;clinically-proven&quot; to treat such symptoms as anxiety, depression, OCD and more.

=== Food ===
{{Library resources box |by=yes |others= |label=Gwyneth Paltrow |viaf=117030333 |wikititle= }}

In October 2007, Paltrow signed for the [[PBS]] television series ''[[Spain... on the Road Again]]'', which showcases [[Spanish cuisine|the food]] and [[culture of Spain]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=Paltrow to make Spain TV series |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7026273.stm |accessdate=December 6, 2007 |date=October 3, 2007 |work=BBC News}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2008, Paltrow co-wrote the book ''Spain... A Culinary Road Trip'' with [[Mario Batali]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last=Reese |first=Jennifer |title=Spain...A Culinary Road Trip|url=https://ew.com/article/2008/10/01/spaina-culinary-road-trip/|work=Entertainment Weekly |date=October 1, 2008|accessdate=December 6, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2011, she wrote a book titled ''My Father's Daughter: Delicious, Easy Recipes Celebrating Family and Togetherness''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=What We're Reading, April 19–25 |url=https://www.npr.org/2011/07/14/135545537/what-were-reading-april-19-25 |newspaper=NPR |date=April 19, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; That same year she penned the book ''Notes From the Kitchen Table''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last=Young |first=Eleanor |title=WIN Gwyneth Paltrow Notes from my Kitchen Table |url=http://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/celebrity/525031/win-gwyneth-paltrow-notes-from-my-kitchen-table.html |newspaper=Marie Claire |date=May 11, 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; Two years later she published a book titled ''It's All Good: Delicious Easy Recipes That Will Make You Look Good and Feel Great'', which promoted an [[elimination diet]] that is unsupported by medical evidence.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|last1=Hoffman|first1=Steven J|last2=Tan|first2=Charlie|title=Biological, psychological and social processes that explain celebrities' influence on patients' health-related behaviors|journal=Archives of Public Health|date=2015|volume=73|issue=1|page=3|doi=10.1186/2049-3258-73-3|pmid=25973193 |pmc=4429495}}&lt;/ref&gt; Included in that book was a recipe for [[avocado toast]] which was widely copied and adapted as part of a [[2010s in food|2010s food trend]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last1=Orenstein|first1=Jayne|title=How the Internet became ridiculously obsessed with avocado toast|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/05/06/how-the-internet-became-ridiculously-obsessed-with-avocado-toast/|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; Also in 2013, Paltrow wrote a foreword for a book by [[Ross Matthews]], ''Man Up! Tales of My Delusional Self-Confidence''. In 2016, Paltrow published a cookbook: ''It's All Easy: Delicious Weekday Recipes for the Super-Busy Home Cook''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last1=Wiedemann |first1=Elettra |title=Gwyneth Paltrow's Avocado Toast Recipe Is Better Than Yours |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2016/04/108113/gwyneth-paltrow-its-all-easy-cookbook-interview |accessdate=February 15, 2019 |work=www.refinery29.com}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Negative reaction by a group of [[scientist]] and [[science communication]] mothers to Paltrow's 2015 video pushing for [[mandatory labelling]] of food containing [[genetically modified organism]]s led to the creation of a [[documentary film|documentary]], ''[[Science Moms]]''. The film is about mothers who advocate for [[science]]-based decision-making concerning the health and [[nutrition]] of children.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last=Miller|first=Matthew |title='Science Moms,' a documentary on 'fact-based parenting,' to screen at MSU |url=https://www.lansingstatejournal.com/story/entertainment/2018/03/19/science-moms-documentary-fact-based-parenting-screen-msu/438694002/|website=Lansingstatejournal.com |publisher=Lansing State Journal|accessdate=March 21, 2018|date=March 19, 2018|quote=It was 2015. Paltrow and company had filmed a video pushing for mandatory labeling of food made with genetically modified organisms. A group of women scientists, science writers and farmers decided to respond.}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Personal life ==
At the age of 24, Paltrow was engaged to actor [[Brad Pitt]], whom she dated from 1994 to 1997.&lt;ref name=Bio /&gt; They called off the engagement, according to Paltrow, because she was not ready for marriage.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://sixtyminutes.ninemsn.com.au/article/259104/gwyneth-in-love |title=Gwyneth in love |work=MSN |date=October 19, 2003 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100707060007/http://sixtyminutes.ninemsn.com.au/article/259104/gwyneth-in-love |archive-date=July 7, 2010 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Paltrow has since said that, as this was her first high-profile relationship with another celebrity, it taught her the need for public discretion about her romantic life.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last=Clehane |first=Diane |title=Beneath the elegance |work=Biography |date=October 2000}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:Gwyneth Paltrow avp Iron Man 3 Paris.jpg|upright|thumb|left|Paltrow at the ''[[Iron Man 3]]'' French premiere in April 2013]]

Paltrow had an on-and-off three-year relationship with actor [[Ben Affleck]] from 1997 to late 2000.&lt;ref name=&quot;Affleck&quot;&gt;{{cite news |last=McClurg |first=Jocelyn |title=Paltrow dishes about Ben, bum |work=[[USA Today]] |date=October 9, 2001}}&lt;/ref&gt; They first broke up in early 1999; soon afterward, Paltrow persuaded Affleck to star in the film ''[[Bounce (film)|Bounce]]'' with her.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last=Lidz |first=Frank |title=Ben Affleck Shocker: I Bargained With Devil for Fame |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/10/movies/film-ben-affleck-shocker-i-bargained-with-devil-for-fame.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 10, 2000}}&lt;/ref&gt; During the making of the film, the couple started dating again and eventually broke up in October 2000.

In October 2002, Paltrow met [[Chris Martin]] of the British band [[Coldplay]] backstage three weeks after the death of her father, [[Bruce Paltrow]]. They married in December 2003 in a ceremony at a hotel in [[Southern California]]. Paltrow was pregnant with Martin's child at the time of their wedding.&lt;ref name=HiscockTele&gt;{{cite news |first=Simon|last=Hiscock|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?view=DETAILS&amp;grid=&amp;xml=/arts/2008/04/30/bfpaltrow130.xml |title=Gwyneth Paltrow: I'm back – and I just love it |accessdate=May 25, 2008 |date=April 30, 2008 |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |location=London, England}}&lt;/ref&gt; Paltrow and Martin have two children together: daughter Apple, born in May 2004,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://people.com/celebrity/its-a-girl-for-gwyneth-paltrow-hubby/|title=It's a Girl for Gwyneth Paltrow &amp; Hubby|accessdate=February 3, 2008|last=Silverman|first=Stephen M.|date=May 14, 2004|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/film/2004/08/27/gwynethpaltrow/ |title=Gwyneth lets Oprah in on the secret of Apple |work=[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]] |date=August 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 21, 2006}}&lt;/ref&gt; and a son Moses, born in April 2006.&lt;ref name=&quot;boy&quot;&gt;{{cite news|url=https://people.com/celebrity/gwyneth-paltrow-has-a-boy/|title=Gwyneth Paltrow Has a Boy|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=April 10, 2006|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/coldplays-quiet-storm-20050825|title=Coldplay's Chris Martin Has a Boy|last=Robertson|first=Jessica|date=April 10, 2006|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=March 24, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Moses' name was inspired by [[Moses (Coldplay song)|a song]] Chris Martin wrote for Paltrow. [[Simon Pegg]] and Martin's bandmate [[Jonny Buckland]] are Apple's godfathers.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/article/martin%20paltrow%20name%20pegg%20as%20godfather_1043099|title=Martin+Paltrow Name Pegg As Godfather|accessdate=March 17, 2009|date=September 9, 2007|website=Contactmusic.com}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Paltrow cut down on work after becoming a mother.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=Second baby on the way for Gwyneth and Chris |url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/film/2006/01/13/gwynethpaltrow/ |work=[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]] |date=January 13, 2006}}&lt;/ref&gt; She also suffered from [[postpartum depression]] after the 2006 birth of her son.&lt;ref name=&quot;depression&quot;&gt;{{cite news|first=Jenny |last=Everett |url=http://www.self.com/health/blogs/healthyself/2011/01/how-gwyneth-beat-the-baby-blue.html |title=Gwyneth Paltrow Opens Up About Postpartum Depression: Could You Be at Risk? |accessdate=February 11, 2011 |date=January 6, 2011 |work=[[Self (magazine)|Self]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110211075220/http://www.self.com/health/blogs/healthyself/2011/01/how-gwyneth-beat-the-baby-blue.html |archive-date=February 11, 2011 }}&lt;/ref&gt; In March 2014, Paltrow announced that she and Martin had separated after ten years of marriage, describing the process as &quot;[[conscious uncoupling]].&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;people.com&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=https://people.com/celebrity/gwyneth-paltrow-and-chris-martin-separate/|title=Gwyneth Paltrow and Chris Martin Separate|first=Mike|last=Fleeman|date=March 25, 2014|accessdate=March 10, 2019|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.goop.com/journal/be/conscious-uncoupling |title=Conscious Uncoupling |website=[[Goop.com]] |date=March 25, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2014 |first=Gwyneth |last=Paltrow}}{{failed verification|date=August 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26742965 |title=Gwyneth Paltrow and Coldplay star Chris Martin to separate |work=[[BBC News]] |date=March 25, 2014 |accessdate=March 26, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; In her official announcement, Paltrow had her doctor, Dr. Habib Sadeghi, and his dentist wife, Dr. Sherry Sami, explain Conscious Uncoupling. A &quot;conscious uncoupling is the ability to understand that every irritation and argument [within a marriage] was a signal to look inside ourselves and identify a negative internal object that needed healing,&quot; Sadeghi explained. &quot;From this perspective, there are no bad guys, just two people, it's about people as individuals, not just the relationship&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/03/26/living/gwyneth-paltrow-conscious-uncoupling-elle/|title=What Gwyneth Paltrow's 'Conscious Uncoupling' really means|last=Natalie|first=Matthews|website=[[CNN]]}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In April 2015, Paltrow filed for divorce,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/gwyneth-paltrow-files-divorce-chris-790481 |title=Gwyneth Paltrow files for divorce from chris martin |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=April 21, 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt; which was finalized on July 14, 2016.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=http://people.com/celebrity/gwyneth-paltrow-and-chris-martin-finalize-their-divorce/|title=Gwyneth Paltrow and Chris Martin Finalize Their Divorce More Than Two Years After Split|first=Kathy Ehrich |last=Dowd |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|location=New York City| date=July 15, 2016|accessdate=November 21, 2017|quote=The duo reached a divorce settlement in May, and their judgment was entered into a Los Angeles County courthouse on Thursday [July 14, 2016].}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2014, Paltrow began dating producer [[Brad Falchuk]], whom she met on the set of ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' in 2010. The couple went public with their relationship in April 2015.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/robert-downey-jrs-50th-birthday-party-was-a-star-studded-affair-201564/ |title=Gwyneth Paltrow, Brad Falchuk Debut Romance at Robert Downey Jr.'s Star-Studded 50th Birthday Party |work=[[Us Magazine]] |date=April 6, 2015 |accessdate=November 22, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; They announced their engagement on January 8, 2018&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/gwyneth-paltrow-confirms-engagement-goop-magazine-cover-1072926|title=Gwyneth Paltrow Confirms Engagement with Goop Magazine Cover|date=January 8, 2018| accessdate=January 8, 2018|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Sam|last=Reed|archive-date=January 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109002757/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/gwyneth-paltrow-confirms-engagement-goop-magazine-cover-1072926 |url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the following July, that they would have a &quot;private and small&quot; wedding.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/how-gwyneth-paltrow-is-prepping-for-her-wedding-to-brad-falchuk/|title=How Gwyneth Paltrow Is Prepping for Her Wedding to Brad Falchuk|date=July 11, 2018|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=July 12, 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/movies/celebrity/how-gwyneth-paltrow-is-prepping-for-her-%E2%80%98small-and-personal%E2%80%99-wedding/ar-AAzVnFl|title=How Gwyneth Paltrow Is Prepping for Her 'Small and Personal' Wedding|website=www.msn.com|accessdate=July 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712121254/https://www.msn.com/en-us/movies/celebrity/how-gwyneth-paltrow-is-prepping-for-her-%E2%80%98small-and-personal%E2%80%99-wedding/ar-AAzVnFl|archive-date=July 12, 2018|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt;
The marriage ceremony was held in September 2018 in [[The Hamptons]] on [[Long Island]], New York. Falchuk had been married since 1994 to Suzanne Bukinik Falchuk, who filed for divorce in 2013.

In 2004, Paltrow practiced [[cupping therapy]], attending a film premiere with bruises on her back.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |title=What caused Gwyneth's spots |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/3879447.stm |accessdate=July 28, 2018 |work=BBC News |date=July 9, 2004}}&lt;/ref&gt; {{as of|2013}}, Paltrow practices [[Transcendental Meditation technique|Transcendental Meditation]].&lt;ref name=NYTfeb13&gt;{{cite news |title=David Lynch Is Back ... as a Guru of Transcendental Meditation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/24/magazine/david-lynch-transcendental-meditation.html |accessdate=February 23, 2013 |newspaper=New York Times |date=February 22, 2013 |first=Claire|last=Hoffman |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130222211638/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/24/magazine/david-lynch-transcendental-meditation.html |archive-date=February 22, 2013 |url-status=dead }}&lt;/ref&gt; While Paltrow had previously smoked one cigarette a week, {{as of|2018|lc=y}} she had cut down.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last=Brodesser-Akner |first=Taffy |title=How Goop's Haters Made Gwyneth Paltrow's Company Worth $250 Million |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/magazine/big-business-gwyneth-paltrow-wellness.html |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 25, 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2017, Paltrow said that during the filming of the 1996 movie ''[[Emma (1996 theatrical film)|Emma]]'', producer [[Harvey Weinstein]] made unwanted sexual advances toward her. She confided in her ex-fiancé Brad Pitt, who confronted Weinstein at an industry event. Weinstein later warned Paltrow not to tell anyone else.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|first1=Jodi|last1=Kantor|first2=Rachel|last2=Abrams|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/10/us/gwyneth-paltrow-angelina-jolie-harvey-weinstein.html|title=Gwyneth Paltrow, Angelina Jolie and Others Say Weinstein Harassed Them|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|location=New York City|date=October 10, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2017, Paltrow was a major source for an article written by ''[[New York Times]]'' investigative journalists [[Jodi Kantor]] and [[Megan Twohey]] about Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|first=Megan C.|last=Hills|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/insider/alist/gwyneth-paltrow-revealed-as-key-player-in-weinstein-investigation-in-explosive-new-book-she-said-a4232851.html|title=Gwyneth Paltrow revealed as key player in Weinstein investigation in new book She Said|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|date=September 11, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In January 2019, retired optometrist Terry Sanderson sued Paltrow for $3.1 million, claiming that three years earlier she collided with him on a ski slope at [[Deer Valley|Deer Valley Resort]] in [[Park City, Utah]], causing him permanent [[traumatic brain injury]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-gwyneth-paltrow-idUSKCN1PO2ML|title=Utah man sues Gwyneth Paltrow for alleged ski slope 'hit and run'|date=January 30, 2019|agency=Reuters|accessdate=February 24, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; Paltrow counter-sued Sanderson in February, claiming that he was the one who crashed into her. She sought a symbolic $1 in damages, as well as repayment of her legal fees.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-gwyneth-paltrow-idUSKCN1Q92TU|title=Gwyneth Paltrow counter-sues Utah man over ski collision, seeks $1|date=February 20, 2019|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=February 24, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|first1=Cole|last1=Delbyck|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/gwyneth-paltrow-is-coutersuing-man-over-ski-and-run-accident-for-1_n_5c700311e4b00eed08336617|title=Gwyneth Paltrow Says She's The Real Victim In Ski Slope Hit-Run|date=February 22, 2019|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=March 13, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;

